  "prompt": "What's the best book of Nietzsche's to start out with?",
  "response": "A great starting point for reading Nietzsche is \"Thus Spoke Zarathustra\" (\"Also Sprach Zarathustra\"). This work is one of his most famous and is written in a poetic and aphoristic style, encapsulating many of his key ideas, including the will to power, the \u00dcbermensch (Overman), and the eternal recurrence.\n\nAnother excellent option is \"Beyond Good and Evil,\" which provides a more systematic exploration of his philosophy and critiques traditional morality. It addresses themes of morality, truth, and the philosophical tradition itself.\n\nIf you're looking for something more introductory, \"Nietzsche: Philosopher, Psychologist, Antichrist\" by Walter Kaufmann offers a helpful guide to Nietzsche's philosophy and context, which can provide valuable insights before diving into the original texts.\n\nUltimately, starting with either \"Thus Spoke Zarathustra\" or \"Beyond Good and Evil\" will give you a strong foundation in Nietzsche's thought.",
